To use reflection for loading and invoking the PageProcessor, you can follow these steps:

1. In your Main class, add a method to load and process the annotations using reflection:

```java
private static void processAnnotations() {
    try {
        Class<?> processorClass = Class.forName("main.Html.Page.PageProcessor.PageProcessor");
        Object processor = processorClass.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();

        Method processMethod = processorClass.getMethod("process", Set.class, RoundEnvironment.class);

        // Create a custom RoundEnvironment
        RoundEnvironment roundEnv = createCustomRoundEnvironment();

        // Invoke the process method
        processMethod.invoke(processor, null, roundEnv);
    } catch (Exception e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    }
}
```

2. Implement a custom RoundEnvironment:

```java
private static RoundEnvironment createCustomRoundEnvironment() {
    return new RoundEnvironment() {
        @Override
        public boolean processingOver() {
            return false;
        }

        @Override
        public boolean errorRaised() {
            return false;
        }

        @Override
        public Set<? extends Element> getRootElements() {
            // Return the set of elements with @Page annotation
            // You'll need to scan your classpath for these
            return findAnnotatedElements();
        }

        @Override
        public Set<? extends Element> getElementsAnnotatedWith(TypeElement a) {
            return null;
        }

        @Override
        public Set<? extends Element> getElementsAnnotatedWith(Class<? extends Annotation> a) {
            return null;
        }
    };
}
```

3. Implement a method to find annotated elements:

```java
private static Set<Element> findAnnotatedElements() {
    Set<Element> elements = new HashSet<>();
    // Scan your classpath for classes with @Page annotation
    // Add them to the elements set
    // You might use a library like Reflections for this
    return elements;
}
```

4. Call the `processAnnotations()` method in your `main` method before starting the server:

```java
public static void main(String[] args) {
    processAnnotations();
    Server.MakeServer(8080);
}
```

This approach allows you to invoke the PageProcessor at runtime, bypassing the need for compile-time processing. Remember to handle exceptions and edge cases appropriately in a production environment.

To use a custom ClassLoader for loading the PageProcessor, you can follow these steps:

1. Create a custom ClassLoader:

```java
public class PageProcessorClassLoader extends ClassLoader {
    @Override
    public Class<?> loadClass(String name) throws ClassNotFoundException {
        if ("main.Html.Page.PageProcessor.PageProcessor".equals(name)) {
            try {
                String className = name.replace('.', '/') + ".class";
                try (InputStream is = getClass().getClassLoader().getResourceAsStream(className)) {
                    byte[] bytes = is.readAllBytes();
                    return defineClass(name, bytes, 0, bytes.length);
                }
            } catch (IOException e) {
                throw new ClassNotFoundException("Error loading PageProcessor", e);
            }
        }
        return super.loadClass(name);
    }
}
```

2. Modify your Main class to use the custom ClassLoader:

```java
package main.Testing;

import main.Server.Server;
import javax.annotation.processing.Processor;
import java.lang.reflect.Method;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        // Load PageProcessor using custom ClassLoader
        ClassLoader loader = new PageProcessorClassLoader();
        Class<?> processorClass = loader.loadClass("main.Html.Page.PageProcessor.PageProcessor");

        // Instantiate PageProcessor
        Processor processor = (Processor) processorClass.getDeclaredConstructor().newInstance();

        // Invoke process method (you'll need to implement logic to gather annotations and create a RoundEnvironment)
        Method processMethod = processorClass.getMethod("process", Set.class, RoundEnvironment.class);
        processMethod.invoke(processor, null, null); // Replace null with actual parameters

        // Start the server
        Server.MakeServer(8080);
    }
}
```

3. Ensure your build process includes the PageProcessor class files in the classpath.

This approach allows you to load the PageProcessor at runtime, separate from the main application code. It gives you flexibility to modify the PageProcessor without recompiling the entire application. Remember to handle exceptions and implement the necessary logic to gather annotations and create a RoundEnvironment for the processor to work with.

