Certainly! For a framework approach, using custom classloading or reflection is an excellent choice. Here's how you can implement these methods:

Custom Classloading:
1. Create a custom ClassLoader that extends ClassLoader
2. Override the loadClass method to intercept class loading
3. In your framework, use this custom ClassLoader to load classes

Here's a basic example:

```java
public class FrameworkClassLoader extends ClassLoader {
    @Override
    public Class<?> loadClass(String name) throws ClassNotFoundException {
        // Your custom logic here
        // You can analyze the class, its annotations, etc.
        return super.loadClass(name);
    }
}
```

Reflection:
1. Create a method in your framework to scan for classes
2. Use reflection to analyze these classes at runtime

Example:

```java
public class FrameworkReflectionUtil {
    public static void processClasses(String packageName) {
        Reflections reflections = new Reflections(packageName);
        Set<Class<?>> annotatedClasses = reflections.getTypesAnnotatedWith(YourAnnotation.class);
        for (Class<?> clazz : annotatedClasses) {
            // Process the class, its methods, fields, etc.
        }
    }
}
```

These approaches allow your framework to dynamically analyze and process classes without relying on the main method or compile-time processing. You can integrate these into your existing framework structure, perhaps as part of an initialization phase or on-demand processing.

The standard Java Reflection API is built into the Java language and doesn't require any additional libraries. However, the `Reflections` class you're trying to use is part of the Reflections library, which is a separate third-party library.

For the built-in Java Reflection API, you don't need to create a `Reflections` object. Instead, you can use classes like `Class`, `Method`, and `Field` directly from the `java.lang.reflect` package.

Here's how you can use the built-in Reflection API to achieve similar functionality:

```java
public class FrameworkReflectionUtil {
    public static void processClasses(String packageName) {
        ClassLoader classLoader = Thread.currentThread().getContextClassLoader();
        String path = packageName.replace('.', '/');
        try {
            Enumeration<URL> resources = classLoader.getResources(path);
            while (resources.hasMoreElements()) {
                URL resource = resources.nextElement();
                File file = new File(resource.getFile());
                for (File classFile : file.listFiles()) {
                    String className = packageName + "." + classFile.getName().replace(".class", "");
                    Class<?> clazz = Class.forName(className);
                    if (clazz.isAnnotationPresent(Page.class)) {
                        processPageAnnotation(clazz);
                    }
                }
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    private static void processPageAnnotation(Class<?> clazz) {
        Page annotation = clazz.getAnnotation(Page.class);
        // Process the annotation similar to how PageProcessor did
        // You can access annotation values like annotation.method(), annotation.path(), etc.
    }
}
```

This approach uses the built-in Reflection API to scan for classes and process annotations, similar to what the PageProcessor was doing.

