These steps will help isolate the cause of the ClassNotFoundException and provide a path to resolving it. The key is to ensure that the runtime environment can locate and load the Home class successfully.

To embed Java code into HTML, you typically don't embed the Java code directly into the HTML file. Instead, you have a few options depending on what you're trying to achieve:

1. Java Applets (Deprecated):
   Java applets used to be a way to embed Java applications in web pages, but they are now deprecated and not supported by modern browsers.

2. JavaScript and Java:
   You can use JavaScript to interact with Java on the server-side. This is typically done through AJAX calls to a Java backend.

3. Java Server Pages (JSP):
   JSP allows you to embed Java code directly into HTML-like files. These are processed on the server and the result is sent to the client as HTML.

4. Servlets:
   Java Servlets can generate HTML content dynamically on the server-side.

Here are examples of the last two approaches:

1. Using JSP:

```jsp
<%@ page language="java" contentType="text/html; charset=UTF-8" pageEncoding="UTF-8"%>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>JSP Example</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Hello from JSP!</h1>
    <%
        // Java code here
        String message = "This is a dynamic message.";
        out.println("<p>" + message + "</p>");

        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            out.println("<p>Line " + i + "</p>");
        }
    %>
</body>
</html>
```

2. Using a Servlet:

```java
import java.io.*;
import javax.servlet.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;

public class HelloServlet extends HttpServlet {
    public void doGet(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
    throws ServletException, IOException {
        response.setContentType("text/html");
        PrintWriter out = response.getWriter();

        out.println("<html>");
        out.println("<head><title>Hello Servlet</title></head>");
        out.println("<body>");
        out.println("<h1>Hello from Servlet!</h1>");

        // Java code to generate dynamic content
        for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            out.println("<p>Line " + i + "</p>");
        }

        out.println("</body></html>");
    }
}
```

Remember, these server-side approaches require a Java web server like Apache Tomcat to run.

If you're looking to run Java code in the browser, that's not typically done. Instead, you might consider using JavaScript, which is the standard language for client-side web programming. If you need Java-like syntax in the browser, you could look into transpiled languages like GWT (Google Web Toolkit) or JSweet, which allow you to write Java code that gets converted to JavaScript.

Programming a templating engine like Thymeleaf from scratch is a complex task, but I can give you an overview of the key components and steps you'd need to consider. This will be a simplified version, but it should give you an idea of the process:

1. Parsing HTML:
   You'd need to parse the HTML file and create a document object model (DOM) or similar structure.

2. Defining custom attributes:
   Create a set of custom attributes (like Thymeleaf's `th:*` attributes) that your engine will recognize.

3. Expression language:
   Develop a simple expression language to evaluate variables and expressions within the template.

4. Context object:
   Create a context object to hold the data that will be used in the template.

5. Attribute processors:
   Implement processors for each custom attribute to handle its specific behavior.

6. Template processing:
   Walk through the DOM, processing each node and its attributes.

Here's a very basic example of how you might start implementing such a system:

```java
import org.jsoup.Jsoup;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Document;
import org.jsoup.nodes.Element;
import org.jsoup.select.Elements;

import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class SimpleTemplateEngine {

    private Map<String, AttributeProcessor> processors = new HashMap<>();

    public SimpleTemplateEngine() {
        // Register processors for custom attributes
        processors.put("s:text", new TextProcessor());
        processors.put("s:each", new EachProcessor());
    }

    public String process(String template, Map<String, Object> context) {
        Document doc = Jsoup.parse(template);
        processElement(doc.body(), context);
        return doc.body().html();
    }

    private void processElement(Element element, Map<String, Object> context) {
        for (AttributeProcessor processor : processors.values()) {
            processor.process(element, context);
        }

        for (Element child : element.children()) {
            processElement(child, context);
        }
    }

    interface AttributeProcessor {
        void process(Element element, Map<String, Object> context);
    }

    class TextProcessor implements AttributeProcessor {
        public void process(Element element, Map<String, Object> context) {
            String attr = "s:text";
            if (element.hasAttr(attr)) {
                String expression = element.attr(attr);
                element.text(evaluateExpression(expression, context));
                element.removeAttr(attr);
            }
        }
    }

    class EachProcessor implements AttributeProcessor {
        public void process(Element element, Map<String, Object> context) {
            String attr = "s:each";
            if (element.hasAttr(attr)) {
                String expression = element.attr(attr);
                // Implementation for loop processing would go here
                element.removeAttr(attr);
            }
        }
    }

    private String evaluateExpression(String expression, Map<String, Object> context) {
        // This is a very simplistic expression evaluator
        // In a real implementation, you'd want a more robust solution
        if (expression.startsWith("${") && expression.endsWith("}")) {
            String key = expression.substring(2, expression.length() - 1);
            return context.get(key).toString();
        }
        return expression;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String template = "<div><p s:text=\"${message}\">Hello</p></div>";
        Map<String, Object> context = new HashMap<>();
        context.put("message", "Hello, World!");

        SimpleTemplateEngine engine = new SimpleTemplateEngine();
        String result = engine.process(template, context);
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
```

This example uses JSoup for HTML parsing, but in a full implementation, you might want to use a different parser or write your own.

Remember, this is a very basic implementation. A full-featured template engine like Thymeleaf would include:

1. More robust expression language
2. More attribute processors
3. Error handling and reporting
4. Caching mechanisms for improved performance
5. Integration with web frameworks
6. Support for internationalization
7. Fragment inclusion and template inheritance

Building a production-ready template engine is a significant undertaking, which is why most developers opt to use existing solutions like Thymeleaf, FreeMarker, or Velocity.

Certainly! Creating a simple template engine using just the Java API is a great learning exercise. Here's a basic implementation that demonstrates the core concepts without using any external libraries:

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileReader;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.regex.Matcher;
import java.util.regex.Pattern;

public class SimpleTemplateEngine {

    private static final Pattern VARIABLE_PATTERN = Pattern.compile("\\$\\{([^}]+)}");
    private static final Pattern EACH_PATTERN = Pattern.compile("<each items=\"\\$\\{([^}]+)}\">(.*?)</each>", Pattern.DOTALL);

    public String render(String templatePath, Map<String, Object> context) throws IOException {
        String template = readFile(templatePath);
        String result = replaceVariables(template, context);
        result = processEachBlocks(result, context);
        return result;
    }

    private String readFile(String filePath) throws IOException {
        StringBuilder content = new StringBuilder();
        try (BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(filePath))) {
            String line;
            while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
                content.append(line).append("\n");
            }
        }
        return content.toString();
    }

    private String replaceVariables(String template, Map<String, Object> context) {
        Matcher matcher = VARIABLE_PATTERN.matcher(template);
        StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer();
        while (matcher.find()) {
            String variable = matcher.group(1);
            Object value = context.get(variable);
            matcher.appendReplacement(sb, value != null ? value.toString() : "");
        }
        matcher.appendTail(sb);
        return sb.toString();
    }

    private String processEachBlocks(String template, Map<String, Object> context) {
        Matcher matcher = EACH_PATTERN.matcher(template);
        StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer();
        while (matcher.find()) {
            String itemsVar = matcher.group(1);
            String blockContent = matcher.group(2);
            List<?> items = (List<?>) context.get(itemsVar);
            StringBuilder replacement = new StringBuilder();
            for (Object item : items) {
                Map<String, Object> itemContext = new HashMap<>(context);
                itemContext.put("item", item);
                replacement.append(replaceVariables(blockContent, itemContext));
            }
            matcher.appendReplacement(sb, replacement.toString());
        }
        matcher.appendTail(sb);
        return sb.toString();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
        SimpleTemplateEngine engine = new SimpleTemplateEngine();

        Map<String, Object> context = new HashMap<>();
        context.put("title", "My Page");
        context.put("name", "John");
        List<String> items = new ArrayList<>();
        items.add("Apple");
        items.add("Banana");
        items.add("Cherry");
        context.put("fruits", items);

        String result = engine.render("template.html", context);
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
```

This implementation provides basic variable substitution and a simple loop construct. Here's how you might use it:

1. Create a template file named `template.html`:

```html
<html>
<head>
    <title>${title}</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome, ${name}!</h1>
    <ul>
    <each items="${fruits}">
        <li>${item}</li>
    </each>
    </ul>
</body>
</html>
```

2. Run the `main` method in the `SimpleTemplateEngine` class.

This implementation:

1. Reads the template file.
2. Replaces variables in the format `${variableName}` with their corresponding values from the context.
3. Processes `<each>` blocks, repeating the content for each item in the specified list.

Key points:

- It uses regular expressions to find variables and loop constructs.
- It's not as feature-rich or efficient as professional template engines, but it demonstrates the basic concepts.
- Error handling is minimal; in a real implementation, you'd want to add more robust error checking and reporting.
- The `<each>` construct is custom and not standard HTML; real template engines often use custom attributes instead.

This basic engine could be extended to include more features like:

- Conditional statements
- Nested loops
- Custom functions
- Include other templates
- Caching of parsed templates for better performance

Remember, this is a simplified example for learning purposes. Real-world template engines are much more complex and optimized for performance and flexibility.

