You're right to notice that issue. The current implementation of the `processEachBlocks` method has a few limitations that are causing the behavior you've observed.

1. The regex pattern for EACH_PATTERN is not capturing nested <each> blocks correctly. It's only capturing the last (innermost) <each> block.

2. The itemsVar is being parsed incorrectly. It's trying to split a string representation of a list, which isn't the correct way to access the actual list objects from the context.

To fix these issues, we need to:

1. Modify the EACH_PATTERN to capture all <each> blocks, including nested ones.
2. Change how we access and iterate over the items in the context.

Here's a suggested improvement for the `processEachBlocks` method:

```java
private String processEachBlocks(String template, Map<String, Object> context) {
    Matcher matcher = EACH_PATTERN.matcher(template);
    StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer();
    while (matcher.find()) {
        String itemsVar = matcher.group(1);
        String blockContent = matcher.group(2);

        Object itemsObj = context.get(itemsVar);
        if (!(itemsObj instanceof List)) {
            continue;
        }

        List<?> items = (List<?>) itemsObj;

        StringBuilder replacement = new StringBuilder();
        for (Object item : items) {
            Map<String, Object> itemContext = new HashMap<>(context);
            itemContext.put("item", item);
            String processedContent = replaceVariables(blockContent, itemContext);
            replacement.append(processedContent);
        }

        matcher.appendReplacement(sb, Matcher.quoteReplacement(replacement.toString()));
    }
    matcher.appendTail(sb);
    return sb.toString();
}
```

This modification should correctly process all <each> blocks, including nested ones, and properly handle the items from the context. It will also correctly replace the ${item} placeholder in each iteration.

To implement a loop that processes all <each> blocks, including nested ones, we can modify the `processEachBlocks` method in the Template class as follows:

```java
private String processEachBlocks(String template, Map<String, Object> context) {
    String result = template;
    boolean found;
    do {
        found = false;
        Matcher matcher = EACH_PATTERN.matcher(result);
        StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer();
        while (matcher.find()) {
            found = true;
            String itemsVar = matcher.group(1);
            String blockContent = matcher.group(2);

            List<?> items = (List<?>) context.get(itemsVar);
            StringBuilder replacement = new StringBuilder();
            for (Object item : items) {
                Map<String, Object> itemContext = new HashMap<>(context);
                itemContext.put("item", item);
                String processedContent = replaceVariables(blockContent, itemContext);
                replacement.append(processedContent);
            }

            matcher.appendReplacement(sb, Matcher.quoteReplacement(replacement.toString()));
        }
        matcher.appendTail(sb);
        result = sb.toString();
    } while (found);

    return result;
}
```

This implementation uses a do-while loop to repeatedly process <each> blocks until no more are found. It will handle nested blocks by processing them in multiple passes, ensuring all blocks are properly expanded.

I understand the current implementation doesn't work as expected. Let's take a different approach to solve this issue. We can modify the EACH_PATTERN to be non-greedy and adjust our processing logic. Here's a potential solution:

```java
private static final Pattern EACH_PATTERN = Pattern.compile("<each\\s+items=\"\\$\\{([^}]+)}\">(.*?)</each>", Pattern.DOTALL);

private String processEachBlocks(String template, Map<String, Object> context) {
    Matcher matcher = EACH_PATTERN.matcher(template);
    StringBuffer sb = new StringBuffer();
    while (matcher.find()) {
        String itemsVar = matcher.group(1);
        String blockContent = matcher.group(2);

        List<?> items = (List<?>) context.get(itemsVar);
        if (items == null) continue;

        StringBuilder replacement = new StringBuilder();
        for (Object item : items) {
            Map<String, Object> itemContext = new HashMap<>(context);
            itemContext.put("item", item);
            String processedContent = replaceVariables(blockContent, itemContext);
            processedContent = processEachBlocks(processedContent, itemContext);
            replacement.append(processedContent);
        }

        matcher.appendReplacement(sb, Matcher.quoteReplacement(replacement.toString()));
    }
    matcher.appendTail(sb);
    return sb.toString();
}
```

This approach should correctly handle nested <each> blocks and process all occurrences in the template.

